2. Creating Your C++ Code:

Let's create a simple C++ program that calculates the factorial of a number:

C++
#include <stdio.h>

int factorial(int n) {
  if (n == 0) {
    return 1;
  } else {
    return n * factorial(n - 1);
  }
}

int main() {
  int num;
  printf("Enter a number: ");
  scanf("%d", &num);

  int result = factorial(num);
  printf("The factorial of %d is %d\n", num, result);

  return 0;
}
Use code with caution.

Save this code as factorial.cpp.

3. Compiling to WebAssembly:

Use the Emscripten compiler (em++) to generate the WebAssembly module:

Bash
em++ factorial.cpp -o factorial.wasm -s WASM=1 -std=c++11
Use code with caution.

Explanation of flags:

  • -o factorial.wasm: Output filename
  • -s WASM=1: Enable WebAssembly generation
  • -std=c++11: Use C++11 standard (adjust if needed)

4. Creating a Simple HTML File:

Create an HTML file (index.html) to load and interact with the WebAssembly module:

HTML
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <title>WebAssembly - Factorial Example</title>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Factorial Calculator</h1>
    <input type="number" id="numberInput">
    <button onclick="calculateFactorial()">Calculate</button>
    <p id="result"></p>

    <script src="factorial.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
Use code with caution.

5. Creating a JavaScript Binding File:

This file (factorial.js) will bridge the communication between JavaScript and the WebAssembly module:

JavaScript
// Import the WebAssembly module
const WASM = import('./factorial.wasm');

async function calculateFactorial() {
  const number = document.getElementById('numberInput').value;
  const intNumber = parseInt(number);

  // Wait for the WebAssembly module to load
  const { factorial } = await WASM;

  // Call the C++ function from JavaScript
  const result = factorial(intNumber);

  // Display the result
  document.getElementById('result').textContent = `The factorial of ${number} is ${result}`;
}
Use code with caution.

Explanation:

  • import('./factorial.wasm'): Imports the WebAssembly module
  • calculateFactorial function:
    • Gets the user input
    • Parses it into an integer
    • Waits for the WASM module to load
    • Calls the factorial function (exported from C++)
    • Displays the result

6. Running the Example in Chrome:

  • Open index.html in Chrome.
  • Enter a number, click "Calculate," and observe the factorial displayed.

Additional Considerations:

  • This is a basic example. For more complex scenarios, you might need to handle memory management, I/O, and other aspects differently.
  • Refer to the Emscripten documentation for advanced usage and troubleshooting: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/WebAssembly/C_to_Wasm

2. Create a Simple C++ File (e.g., add.cpp):

C++
#include <stdio.h>

int add(int a, int b) {
    return a + b;
}

int main() {
    int x = 5;
    int y = 10;
    int result = add(x, y);
    printf("The sum of %d and %d is %d\n", x, y, result);
    return 0;
}
Use code with caution.

This code defines a function add that takes two integers and returns their sum. The main function demonstrates its usage.

3. Compile C++ to WebAssembly:

Use the Emscripten compiler (emcc) to generate the WebAssembly module (add.wasm) and a boilerplate JavaScript file (add.html):

Bash
emcc add.cpp -o add.wasm -s WASM=1 -s SIDE_MODULE=1
Use code with caution.

Explanation of flags:

  • -o add.wasm: Output filename for the WebAssembly module.
  • -s WASM=1: Force generation of WebAssembly code.
  • -s SIDE_MODULE=1: Create a separate JavaScript file for library functions.

4. Create a Simple HTML File (e.g., index.html):

HTML
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <title>WebAssembly Example</title>
</head>
<body>
    <script src="add.html"></script>
    <script>
        Module['onRuntimeInitialized'] = function() {
            var result = Module.ccall('add', 'number', ['number', 'number'], 5, 10);
            console.log("The sum is:", result);
        };
    </script>
</body>
</html>
Use code with caution.

This HTML file includes the generated add.html (which configures the WebAssembly module) and sets up a callback function to be invoked when the module is initialized. The callback then calls the exported add function from WebAssembly using Module.ccall and logs the result to the console.

5. Run the Example in Chrome:

Open a terminal, navigate to the directory containing the files (index.html, add.wasm, and add.html), and start a local development server using Python's http.server:

Bash
python3 -m http.server 8000
Use code with caution.

Then, open Chrome and navigate to http://localhost:8000/index.html. You should see the console output:

The sum is: 15

This demonstrates how C++ code can be compiled into WebAssembly and executed within the browser environment, interacting with JavaScript for seamless integration.

2. Creating the C++ Code:

Let's create a simple C++ program that adds two numbers:

C++
#include <stdio.h>

int add(int a, int b) {
  return a + b;
}

int main() {
  int x = 5;
  int y = 10;
  int result = add(x, y);
  printf("The sum of %d and %d is %d\n", x, y, result);
  return 0;
}
Use code with caution.

Save this code as add.cpp.

3. Compiling to WebAssembly:

Use the em++ compiler from Emscripten to compile the C++ code:

Bash
em++ add.cpp -o add.wasm -s WASM=1 -s SIDE_MODULE=1
Use code with caution.

Explanation of flags:

  • -o add.wasm: Output filename
  • -s WASM=1: Enable WebAssembly output
  • -s SIDE_MODULE=1: Create a separate JavaScript file for library functions

4. Creating the HTML File:

Create an HTML file (index.html) to load and interact with the WebAssembly module:

HTML
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
<title>WebAssembly Example</title>
</head>
<body>
  <script src="add.js"></script>
  <script>
    Module.then(function(Module) {
      var result = Module.ccall('add', 'number', ['number', 'number'], 5, 10);
      console.log("The sum is:", result);
    });
  </script>
</body>
</html>
Use code with caution.

Explanation:

  • The script tag loads the generated JavaScript file (add.js).
  • The Module.then function waits for the WebAssembly module to load.
  • Module.ccall calls the exported C++ function (add).

5. Running the Example:

Open index.html in Chrome and open the browser console (usually F12 or Ctrl + Shift + I). You should see the output:

The sum is: 15

Additional Notes:

  • This is a basic example. For more complex scenarios, you might need to handle memory management and data types carefully.
  • Consider exploring Emscripten's documentation for detailed information and advanced features: https://emscripten.org/docs/compiling/index.html

I'd be glad to guide you through creating a WebAssembly example in C++ for Chrome on Linux:

1. Setting Up Emscripten:

Emscripten is a popular toolchain for compiling C/C++ code to WebAssembly. Here's how to install it:

Bash
# Download the latest Emscripten SDK
wget https://github.com/emscripten-core/emscripten/archive/sdk-2.0.x.tar.gz

# Extract the archive
tar -xf sdk-2.0.x.tar.gz

# Set up the environment (replace `EMSCRIPTEN_ROOT` with the actual path)
export EMSCRIPTEN_ROOT=path/to/emscripten/sdk-2.0.x
source ${EMSCRIPTEN_ROOT}/emsdk_setup.sh
Use code with caution.
